This paper is about a new family of consensus protocols for distributed networks with guaranteed Byzantine fault tolerance. The paper discusses the use of directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) and concurrent common knowledge to achieve consensus. These topics are typically studied in the computer science sub-categories of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Cryptography and Security (cs.CR), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), Systems and Control (cs.SY), and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI). Therefore, these are the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories for this paper, ordered from most to least likely.
